name: Structural Integrity
description: The Federation flagship is a symbol of everything it stands for. But despite the many variants of the Enterprise in the present, the prime version is showing its age. And there may be something even more sinister lurking just beneath the hood.
rules:
-- Unique Supply Missions are available during the event. Open the Event to access them.
-- Using any version of Kirk, La'an, Chapel, or Explorers will provide a bonus to Supply Missions.
-- Every Supply Mission you complete earns you Event Victory Points. Collect Event Victory Points to unlock Threshold Rewards!
-- Community Rewards are only available during Phase 1. Collect Event Victory Points to unlock these rewards before the phase change!
-- In this event, Squadrons may also compete to advance up the Squadron leaderboards. Join a Squadron to get more rewards!
bonus_text: Crew Bonus: Kirk, La'an, Chapel, or Explorers
rewards_teaser: Reach Rank 1 by gaining Victory Points from Event Supply Missions!

featured_crew.name: Pike
featured_crew.flavor: Intent on being more than just a pretty face, Pike proved himself just as brutal as any other mirror denizen, including in how he took command of the ISS Enterprise.

featured_crew.name: La'an
featured_crew.flavor: La’an’s gratitude to Una for saving her life shows as she speaks up on her friend and crewmate’s behalf.

screens.text: "Remarkable to think that after all these years, so many ships have borne the name Enterprise. At the same time, looking at the hell the E has been through, I'm surprised we're not further down the alphabet! Surely there must be something we can do for her!"

"I heard they were hoping to have her on-hand for an upcoming diplomatic conference, but even the surface repairs would take more time and resources than Starfleet has available. So it sounds like they'll be using an alternate Enterprise brought to this time."
"It's ridiculous really. If the E is the Enterprise of this time, then it's the E we should be showing off. I bet you could round up the manpower to get her fixed up, couldn't you, Captain?"

"Remarkable to think that after all these years, so many ships have borne the name Enterprise. At the same time, looking at the hell the E has been through, I'm surprised we're not further down the alphabet! Surely there must be something we can do for her!"

"I heard they were hoping to have her on-hand for an upcoming diplomatic conference, but even the surface repairs would take more time and resources than Starfleet has available. So it sounds like they'll be using an alternate Enterprise brought to this time."
"It's ridiculous really. If the E is the Enterprise of this time, then it's the E we should be showing off. I bet you could round up the manpower to get her fixed up, couldn't you, Captain?"

"Strong work, Captain, now that's an Enterprise worth showing off! I still can't believe this ship was under the command of a Klingon. I suppose that's a testament to how far the Federation has come."

responses.text: "I'm sorry, I don't recall seeing anything unusual."
"I thought the worst thing we found was that opera Captain Worf was composing."

screens.text: "Sorry to break up the celebrating and kudos, but we've a slight problem. I was just reviewing the logs from your sweeps of the computers. It would appear we have a little security issue on our hands."

"There's all manner of Starfleet intel in the memory banks regarding other factions. And I don't mean normal intel. I mean this is Starfleet Intelligence-level classified information. Not only that, but it's been accessed remotely several times. This is serious."

"You wouldn't unless you knew what to look for. It's not the first time, which is why I asked you to sweep. Classified intel on other factions is popping up on computers of decommissioned or out of service ships. We think someone may be using them to pass intel remotely."
"...yes, well, I wasn't going to comment on that. I did leave Captain Worf's...artistic work untouched."

"Word has already reached some of the impacted factions regarding this security breach. They've insisted on having some of their own involved. We can deal with the optics if you can handle the practicalities."
